{
  "cert_id": "iso27001_li",
  "domain_id": "annex_a_controls",
  "quiz_num": 5,
  "domain_name": "Controles Anexo A — ISO 27002",
  "cert_name": "ISO 27001 Lead Implementer",
  "lang": "en",
  "questions": [
    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022, which statement correctly defines the primary purpose of an Information Security Management System (ISMS)?",
      "tag": "ISMS_Fundamentals",
      "options": [
        "C. To ensure compliance with regulatory requirements only",
        "D. To transfer all security risks to third-party insurance providers",
        "B. To eliminate all information security threats from the organization's IT infrastructure",
        "A. To establish, implement, maintain and continually improve an organization's ability to manage information security risks"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 4.1 defines ISMS as a systematic approach to manage information security through risk identification, assessment, and treatment, enabling continuous improvement aligned with organizational objectives.",
      "justification_wrong": "Complete threat elimination is unrealistic; ISMS focuses on risk management, not elimination. Compliance is a benefit, not the primary purpose. Risk transfer is one mitigation option among many."
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "In ISO 27002:2022, the 93 controls are organized into four main categories. Which category contains controls related to access management and cryptography?",
      "tag": "Control_Categories",
      "options": [
        "C. Physical controls",
        "D. Technological controls",
        "A. Organizational controls",
        "B. People controls"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 designates 34 technological controls addressing technical safeguards including access control (8.2, 8.3), cryptography (8.1), and system security (8.24-8.34).",
      "justification_wrong": "Organizational controls (37) focus on policies and governance. People controls (8) address awareness and competence. Physical controls (14) manage facilities and equipment protection, not technical access mechanisms."
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "Which of the following best describes the concept of 'risk appetite' as referenced in ISO 27001:2022?",
      "tag": "Risk_Management",
      "options": [
        "C. The total number of information security incidents permitted annually",
        "A. The organization's willingness to accept risks that align with its strategic objectives and values",
        "D. The percentage of IT budget allocated to security controls",
        "B. The maximum financial loss an organization can tolerate before operational failure"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1 establishes risk appetite as the organization's acceptance of risk types and levels supporting strategic goals, guiding risk treatment decisions and resource allocation.",
      "justification_wrong": "Risk appetite is not merely financial thresholds, nor incident quotas, nor budget percentages. It represents qualitative organizational tolerance for residual risk across information security domains."
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "text": "Under ISO 27001:2022, what is the primary responsibility of the organization's top management regarding the ISMS?",
      "tag": "Management_Responsibility",
      "options": [
        "D. Annual reporting of security metrics to external auditors only",
        "A. Delegating all ISMS decisions exclusively to the Information Security Officer",
        "C. Outsourcing information security operations to external consultants",
        "B. Demonstrating leadership and commitment by ensuring establishment, implementation, maintenance, and continual improvement of the ISMS"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 5.1 mandates top management leadership demonstrating commitment through resource allocation, policy establishment, integration with business processes, and accountability for ISMS effectiveness.",
      "justification_wrong": "Delegation without accountability violates stewardship principles. Outsourcing transfers execution, not responsibility. External reporting alone does not fulfill internal accountability requirements for ISMS governance."
    },
    {
      "num": 5,
      "text": "Which ISO 27002:2022 organizational control addresses the need to establish guidelines for acceptable use of organizational assets?",
      "tag": "Organizational_Controls",
      "options": [
        "B. Control 5.3 - Segregation of duties",
        "C. Control 5.16 - Management of information security incidents",
        "D. Control 5.23 - Information security for supplier relationships",
        "A. Control 5.1 - Policies for information security"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 5.1 requires organizations to establish, publish, and communicate information security policies including acceptable use of information and assets, forming the foundation for organizational governance.",
      "justification_wrong": "Control 5.3 addresses role separation, 5.16 focuses on incident response procedures, and 5.23 governs third-party relationships. None directly establish asset usage guidelines as comprehensively as policy framework controls."
    },
    {
      "num": 6,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022, which of the following best describes the primary purpose of establishing an Information Security Management System (ISMS)?",
      "tag": "ISMS Fundamentals",
      "options": [
        "D. To implement the maximum number of security controls regardless of organizational context",
        "B. To comply exclusively with legal and regulatory requirements in all jurisdictions",
        "A. To protect information assets through systematic risk management and ensure confidentiality, integrity, and availability",
        "C. To eliminate all security risks and threats completely"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 4.1 establishes ISMS purpose as managing information security through risk-based approach, ensuring CIA principles. It's systematic, proportionate, and context-driven.",
      "justification_wrong": "Sole legal compliance (B) ignores business objectives; eliminating all risks (C) is impossible; maximum controls (D) contradicts proportionality principle in ISO 27001."
    },
    {
      "num": 7,
      "text": "In ISO 27001:2022, the control 'Segregation of Duties' is classified under which control domain, and what is its primary objective?",
      "tag": "Organizational Controls",
      "options": [
        "C. Technological Controls; to encrypt data transmission channels",
        "B. Organizational Controls; to prevent conflicts of interest and reduce fraud risk",
        "D. People Controls; to ensure employee awareness training completion",
        "A. Physical Controls; to prevent unauthorized physical access to facilities"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 5.16 (Segregation of Duties) is organizational. It prevents individuals from performing incompatible functions simultaneously, reducing fraud and error risk through role separation.",
      "justification_wrong": "A refers to physical access; C describes cryptography; D relates to awareness. SOD is administrative/organizational principle preventing conflicts of interest."
    },
    {
      "num": 8,
      "text": "Which of the following statements regarding ISO 27001:2022 Annex A controls and ISO 27002:2022 implementation guidance is most accurate?",
      "tag": "Control Framework Relationship",
      "options": [
        "B. Annex A lists control objectives; ISO 27002 provides detailed guidance, implementation considerations, and additional information",
        "C. ISO 27002 controls supersede Annex A and must always be implemented in full",
        "A. Annex A provides detailed implementation steps; ISO 27002 provides only high-level control objectives",
        "D. Annex A and ISO 27002 cover entirely different control domains with no overlap"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Annex A lists 93 controls with objectives. ISO 27002:2022 provides comprehensive implementation guidance, considerations, and supplementary information for each control.",
      "justification_wrong": "A reverses relationship; C ignores risk-based selection principle; D is incorrect—ISO 27002 expands Annex A controls with practical guidance."
    },
    {
      "num": 9,
      "text": "During ISMS risk assessment per ISO 27001:2022, which element is NOT a core component of the risk analysis process?",
      "tag": "Risk Management Process",
      "options": [
        "C. Establishing marketing strategies for competitive advantage",
        "B. Determining probability and impact of potential threats and vulnerabilities",
        "D. Evaluating existing controls and their effectiveness",
        "A. Identifying assets and their value to the organization"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Marketing strategy (C) is unrelated to information security risk analysis. ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1.2 requires asset identification, threat/vulnerability analysis, and control evaluation.",
      "justification_wrong": "A, B, D are essential risk analysis components per ISO 27001:2022. Assets (A), probability/impact (B), and control evaluation (D) form risk assessment foundation."
    },
    {
      "num": 10,
      "text": "According to ISO 27002:2022, which control measure is classified as a 'Technological Control' and directly addresses data protection?",
      "tag": "Technological Controls - Data Protection",
      "options": [
        "D. Information security policy development and approval process",
        "C. Physical access badges and facility perimeter fencing",
        "B. Encryption of sensitive data at rest and in transit",
        "A. Personnel screening and background verification procedures"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 8.1 (Cryptography) is technological, protecting data confidentiality/integrity through encryption. Directly addresses CIA principles through technical mechanisms.",
      "justification_wrong": "A is People Control; C is Physical Control; D is Organizational Control. Only encryption (B) represents technological data protection implementation."
    },
    {
      "num": 11,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022 and ISO 27002:2022, which control category addresses the need to identify and classify information assets before implementing protection measures?",
      "tag": "Asset Management & Classification",
      "options": [
        "C. Physical control for facility access restrictions",
        "A. Organizational control for information and asset management (5.9)",
        "B. Technological control for encryption mechanisms",
        "D. Personnel control for security awareness training"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 5.9 establishes organizational context for asset management. ISO 27002:2022 controls 5.9 (information and asset management) require identifying, inventorying, and classifying information assets as foundational to implementing appropriate controls.",
      "justification_wrong": "Encryption (B), physical access (C), and training (D) are derived controls applied after asset classification. They depend on understanding what assets require protection, not the classification process itself."
    },
    {
      "num": 12,
      "text": "In an ISO 27001:2022 ISMS, which control from the People domain ensures that security responsibilities are clearly communicated before employees begin work?",
      "tag": "Personnel Security & Responsibilities",
      "options": [
        "C. A.7.2 – Terms and conditions of employment",
        "A. A.6.2 – Information security roles and responsibilities",
        "B. A.7.1 – Screening and background verification",
        "D. A.8.1 – Prior to employment"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 control 6.2 establishes that all personnel must understand their security roles and responsibilities. This aligns with ISO 27002:2022 guidance on clear assignment before employment or access to assets.",
      "justification_wrong": "Screening (B) verifies background; terms (C) document expectations; and prior-to-employment (D) is a timing control. None directly define role clarity as control A.6.2 does."
    },
    {
      "num": 13,
      "text": "Which physical security control from ISO 27002:2022 addresses the protection of facilities against unauthorized physical access and environmental threats?",
      "tag": "Physical & Environmental Security",
      "options": [
        "D. Control 6.7 – Threat intelligence and vulnerability management",
        "C. Control 5.15 – Access control policies and enforcement",
        "B. Control 8.1 – Cryptographic controls for data protection",
        "A. Control 7.1 – Physical security perimeters"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 control 7.1 specifies physical security perimeters, barriers, and access points to prevent unauthorized entry and environmental damage. This is the foundational physical security control.",
      "justification_wrong": "Cryptographic controls (B) are technological; access control policies (C) are organizational; threat intelligence (D) is technological. None address the physical perimeter itself."
    },
    {
      "num": 14,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022, what is the primary purpose of conducting an information security risk assessment during the organization's context determination phase?",
      "tag": "Risk Assessment & Management",
      "options": [
        "D. To assign responsibility for incident response procedures",
        "B. To determine the scope and boundaries of the ISMS",
        "A. To identify, analyze, and evaluate risks to information security objectives",
        "C. To select and implement all 93 controls from ISO 27002:2022"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1.2 requires risk assessment to identify, analyze, and evaluate risks. This informs risk treatment decisions and control selection, aligning with Clauses 6.1.3 and 6.2.",
      "justification_wrong": "Scope determination (B) precedes risk assessment; implementing all controls (C) is not required—only necessary ones; incident response (D) is a treatment outcome, not the primary assessment purpose."
    },
    {
      "num": 15,
      "text": "In ISO 27001:2022, which clause requires organizations to establish and maintain procedures for monitoring, measuring, analyzing, and evaluating the effectiveness of the ISMS?",
      "tag": "Monitoring & Continuous Improvement",
      "options": [
        "B. Clause 9.1 – Monitoring, measurement, analysis, and evaluation",
        "A. Clause 8 – Operation and management of the ISMS",
        "D. Clause 7 – Support, resources, and competence",
        "C. Clause 10 – Improvement activities and corrective actions"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 9.1 specifically requires organizations to monitor and measure ISMS effectiveness through performance indicators, audit results, and management review, feeding into continuous improvement.",
      "justification_wrong": "Clause 8 covers operational procedures; Clause 10 addresses corrective actions based on findings; Clause 7 focuses on resource allocation. Clause 9.1 is the explicit monitoring and evaluation requirement."
    },
    {
      "num": 16,
      "text": "According to ISO 27001:2022 and ISO 27002:2022, which control objective directly addresses the management of information security risks arising from third-party relationships and supply chain dependencies?",
      "tag": "Supplier Relationships & Risk Management",
      "options": [
        "D. Control 8.34 - Monitoring activities",
        "C. Control 6.7 - Threat intelligence and information sharing",
        "B. Control 5.12 - Management of removable media",
        "A. Control 5.19 - Addressing information security in supplier relationships"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 5.19 explicitly addresses supplier information security management, risk assessment, and contractual arrangements. This organizational control ensures third-party security alignment with organization requirements, mitigating supply chain vulnerabilities.",
      "justification_wrong": "Control 5.12 concerns removable media handling; 6.7 addresses threat intelligence; 8.34 focuses on monitoring. None directly manage supplier relationship risks as comprehensively as 5.19."
    },
    {
      "num": 17,
      "text": "In implementing ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6 (Planning), an organization must conduct risk assessments. Which statement accurately reflects the relationship between risk assessment scope and the information security perimeter?",
      "tag": "Risk Assessment & Scope Definition",
      "options": [
        "B. Risk assessment scope must align exactly with the information security perimeter defined in Clause 4.3",
        "C. Risk assessment scope is independent of the information security perimeter and determined solely by threat landscape",
        "A. Risk assessment scope must be broader than the information security perimeter to identify external threats",
        "D. Risk assessment scope should exclude cloud-based assets as they fall outside organizational control"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1 requires risk assessment within the information security perimeter established in Clause 4.3. The scope must be consistent with organizational context boundaries to ensure complete coverage of relevant assets and vulnerabilities.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A conflates scope with external factors; C ignores perimeter alignment; D incorrectly excludes cloud assets. Clause 6.1 mandates perimeter-aligned scope determination."
    },
    {
      "num": 18,
      "text": "An organization implements ISO 27002:2022 Control 6.1 (Screening) for personnel selection. Which factor is NOT a valid component of background verification according to the control's objectives and guidance?",
      "tag": "Personnel Security & Screening",
      "options": [
        "C. Prediction of future organizational loyalty using predictive analytics without consent",
        "B. Verification of criminal history proportional to role sensitivity",
        "D. Reference checks from previous employers or educational institutions",
        "A. Verification of professional qualifications and credentials"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 6.1 requires factual verification (qualifications, criminal records, references). Predictive analytics for loyalty determination lacks objective basis, violates privacy principles, and contradicts screening's evidence-based nature.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options A, B, D are explicit screening components. Option C introduces unauthorized predictive methods incompatible with control intent and privacy legislation (GDPR alignment)."
    },
    {
      "num": 19,
      "text": "Regarding ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.3 (Determination of scope) and ISO 27002:2022 Controls 7.1-7.14 (Physical controls), which statement correctly describes the relationship between scope documentation and physical security implementation?",
      "tag": "Scope Documentation & Physical Controls",
      "options": [
        "A. Physical controls apply only to assets explicitly listed in the scope statement and not to supporting infrastructure",
        "B. Scope documentation must identify all assets requiring protection; physical controls protect assets and supporting infrastructure within the defined perimeter",
        "C. Physical controls are independent of scope and apply uniformly to all organizational buildings regardless of scope definition",
        "D. Physical security requirements are determined post-implementation after control selection, not during scope definition"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.3 defines scope; supporting infrastructure within perimeter requires physical controls per ISO 27002:2022 Section 7. Scope boundaries determine which physical controls (7.1-7.14) apply, ensuring comprehensive asset and infrastructure protection.",
      "justification_wrong": "A contradicts infrastructure protection necessity; C ignores scope-based risk differentiation; D violates systematic planning sequence. Scope precedes control application per ISO 27001 structure."
    },
    {
      "num": 20,
      "text": "An organization implements ISO 27001:2022 and must establish the relationship between risk treatment options (accept, mitigate, avoid, share) and the control selection process per Clause 6.2. Which scenario represents incorrect application?",
      "tag": "Risk Treatment & Control Selection",
      "options": [
        "D. Risk sharing chosen; organization transfers risk via insurance while maintaining preventive technical controls",
        "C. Risk acceptance chosen; organization documents and approves residual risk exceeding risk criteria without control implementation",
        "B. Risk mitigation chosen; organization selects ISO 27002 controls to reduce risk to acceptable level below risk criteria",
        "A. Risk avoidance chosen; organization discontinues service line entirely rather than implementing compensating controls"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.2 permits risk acceptance only when residual risk remains within defined criteria. Option C violates this requirement—accepting risk above criteria contradicts Clause 6.1.3 risk criteria establishment, lacking justified rationale.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options A, B, D represent valid treatment applications. A demonstrates avoidance; B shows mitigation; D demonstrates sharing with dual controls. All comply with Clause 6.2 risk treatment principles."
    },
    {
      "num": 21,
      "text": "In ISO 27001:2022, when establishing an Information Security Management System (ISMS), which control from the Organizational theme directly addresses the requirement to define roles, responsibilities, and authorities for information security decisions?",
      "tag": "ISMS Governance Structure",
      "options": [
        "A. Control 5.1 - Policies for information security",
        "C. Control 5.2 - Information security policy review",
        "D. Control 8.1 - Screening and background checks",
        "B. Control 6.1 - Information security roles and responsibilities"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Control 6.1 explicitly requires establishing and communicating roles, responsibilities, and authorities for information security. This is fundamental organizational control enabling decision-making authority and accountability across the ISMS as per ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.",
      "justification_wrong": "While 5.1 establishes policy direction and 5.2 reviews effectiveness, neither specifically defines organizational roles and responsibilities. Control 8.1 addresses personnel screening, not governance structure."
    },
    {
      "num": 22,
      "text": "During an ISMS audit, you identify that cryptographic controls are implemented but lack documented procedures for key management lifecycle (generation, storage, rotation, and destruction). Which ISO 27002:2022 control is not adequately implemented?",
      "tag": "Cryptographic Key Management",
      "options": [
        "B. Control 10.2 - Cryptographic key management",
        "C. Control 8.4 - Disciplinary process",
        "A. Control 10.1 - Cryptography",
        "D. Control 9.2 - User access management"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Control 10.2 specifically addresses cryptographic key management including generation, storage, access, rotation, and destruction. The absence of documented lifecycle procedures indicates non-conformity with ISO 27002:2022 requirements for managing cryptographic keys throughout their lifecycle.",
      "justification_wrong": "Control 10.1 covers cryptography implementation but not key management lifecycle. Controls 8.4 and 9.2 address discipline and user access respectively, not cryptographic key management procedures."
    },
    {
      "num": 23,
      "text": "An organization implements an incident response procedure requiring all security incidents to be reported within 4 hours. However, the procedure lacks clear definition of what constitutes a reportable incident and lacks escalation paths. Which control deficiency requires immediate remediation per ISO 27001:2022?",
      "tag": "Incident Management Deficiencies",
      "options": [
        "B. Control 8.16 - Management of information security incidents",
        "A. Control 5.23 - Information security incident management and improvements",
        "C. Control 5.25 - Responses to information security incidents",
        "D. Control 8.35 - Information security incident response planning"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Control 8.16 requires defining what constitutes an incident, assessment procedures, response actions, and escalation paths. The missing incident definition and escalation routes directly violate ISO 27002:2022 requirements for incident management implementation.",
      "justification_wrong": "Control 5.23 covers post-incident improvements. Control 5.25 addresses response coordination. Control 8.35 focuses on planning. None comprehensively address the immediate deficiency in incident definition and escalation structure."
    },
    {
      "num": 24,
      "text": "When implementing physical security controls per ISO 27002:2022, an organization must balance access control with emergency response capabilities. Which combination of controls best satisfies this dual requirement?",
      "tag": "Physical Security Integration",
      "options": [
        "A. Control 11.1 (Physical boundaries) + Control 11.2 (Physical entry)",
        "B. Control 11.2 (Physical entry) + Control 11.3 (Securing and returning assets)",
        "D. Control 11.4 (Monitoring) + Control 11.7 (Clear desk and clear screen)",
        "C. Control 11.2 (Physical entry) + Control 11.5 (Access to buildings and other facilities)"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Control 11.1 establishes perimeter security with emergency egress provisions; Control 11.2 implements access control mechanisms allowing emergency override. Together they satisfy both access restriction and emergency response requirements per ISO 27002:2022 Physical controls theme.",
      "justification_wrong": "11.3 addresses asset handling; 11.5 duplicates 11.2 functionality; 11.4 and 11.7 address monitoring and housekeeping, neither addressing emergency response capability or balancing access control comprehensively."
    },
    {
      "num": 25,
      "text": "In an ISO 27001:2022 ISMS implementation, the organization establishes a control environment but fails to document the relationship between business objectives, information security requirements, and selected controls. What is the primary risk of this gap?",
      "tag": "Risk-Based Control Selection",
      "options": [
        "A. Controls may not address actual organizational risks and compliance requirements",
        "D. The organization cannot renew its ISO 27001 certification",
        "B. The auditor cannot verify control implementation timelines",
        "C. Personnel cannot complete annual security awareness training"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1 and 6.2 require risk-based control selection with documented traceability. Without mapping business objectives to information security requirements to controls, the ISMS lacks systematic risk management foundation, risking inadequate protection.",
      "justification_wrong": "B addresses audit procedures; C concerns personnel training unrelated to objective-control traceability; D oversimplifies certification impact. The core issue is inadequate risk-based control justification per ISO 27001:2022 methodology."
    },
    {
      "num": 26,
      "text": "During an ISO 27001:2022 implementation, an organization must establish Risk Assessment and Treatment processes. According to Annex A, which control theme addresses the foundational governance requirement for Information Security Risk Management?",
      "tag": "Risk Management Framework",
      "options": [
        "D. Technological controls (Theme 4) implementing cryptographic mechanisms",
        "A. Organizational controls (Theme 1) that establish governance, strategy, and risk management policies",
        "B. People controls (Theme 2) focused on security awareness and training programs",
        "C. Physical controls (Theme 3) for facility access and environmental protection"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.1 and Annex A (5.1-5.7) establish that organizational controls provide governance frameworks, risk assessment methodologies, and treatment planning—foundational to ISMS. Risk management is a governance responsibility.",
      "justification_wrong": "People, physical, and technological controls support risk management implementation but do not establish the foundational governance framework or risk assessment processes required in Clause 6."
    },
    {
      "num": 27,
      "text": "An organization implements Access Control mechanisms per ISO 27002:2022. When designing User Access Management (Technological Theme, Control 8.2), which principle BEST ensures alignment with ISO 27001:2022 requirements?",
      "tag": "Access Control Implementation",
      "options": [
        "C. Implementing role-based access without formal user provisioning procedures",
        "D. Using only administrative passwords managed by IT without encryption requirements",
        "B. Granting maximum permissions to reduce operational friction and support user productivity",
        "A. Principle of least privilege with periodic access reviews documented in the Statement of Applicability (SoA)"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 8.2.1 mandates least privilege with periodic formal reviews. ISO 27001:2022 requires documented control justifications in SoA. This ensures technical implementation aligns with governance documentation requirements.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options B, C, D violate least privilege principles, lack formal procedures, and ignore encryption/administrative controls mandated by ISO 27002:2022 Section 8 (Technological controls)."
    },
    {
      "num": 28,
      "text": "During an internal audit of ISO 27001:2022 compliance, the auditor discovers that the organization's Cryptographic Controls (ISO 27002:2022, Control 10.1) lack a documented Key Management Policy. What is the MOST appropriate corrective action classification?",
      "tag": "Cryptographic Controls & Audit",
      "options": [
        "C. Minor finding: Implement encryption immediately without formal documentation",
        "B. Observation: Key management is optional for organizations using cloud providers",
        "A. Non-conformity: Control 10.1 requires documented encryption key management; absence violates Annex A and Clause 8.1 (Planning) requirements",
        "D. No action required: Encryption hardware vendor manages keys automatically"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27002:2022 Control 10.1.1 explicitly requires cryptographic key management documented in organizational policies. ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.1 mandates planning for controls. Absence is a non-conformity requiring corrective action.",
      "justification_wrong": "Cloud provider responsibility, vendor management, or lack of documentation do not exempt organizations from establishing formal key management policies per ISO 27001/27002 requirements."
    },
    {
      "num": 29,
      "text": "An organization conducts a Control Modification Risk Assessment when implementing a new Data Loss Prevention (DLP) tool (ISO 27002:2022, Control 8.3—Information Security in Project Management). Per ISO 27001:2022, what must be included in the documented assessment?",
      "tag": "Change Management & Control Modification",
      "options": [
        "B. Only IT department sign-off without documented risk re-assessment",
        "D. Implementation schedule without evaluating security posture changes",
        "C. Vendor's risk assessment report as sole evidence of compliance",
        "A. Impact analysis, residual risk re-evaluation, stakeholder approval, and Statement of Applicability updates with justifications"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 6.2 requires documented risk treatment decisions. ISO 27002:2022 Control 8.3 mandates control modifications documented with impact analysis, residual risk, and SoA justifications reflecting organizational context and stakeholder governance.",
      "justification_wrong": "Vendor reports alone, IT-only decisions, or unassessed implementations violate ISO 27001:2022 requirements for documented risk management and organizational governance over control changes."
    },
    {
      "num": 30,
      "text": "During ISO 27001:2022 certification audit, the lead auditor reviews the organization's response to a Critical Security Incident affecting Incident Management (ISO 27002:2022, Control 8.6—Incident Management). Which evidence demonstrates BEST conformity with ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.2 (Implementation)?",
      "tag": "Incident Management & Demonstration of Implementation",
      "options": [
        "D. Regulatory report submitted to authorities without internal documentation",
        "C. IT manager verbal explanation of incident handling during audit interview",
        "A. Documented incident response procedure, incident log with timeline, forensic evidence, post-incident review report, and control effectiveness improvements implemented",
        "B. Email notification to users stating incident occurred"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "ISO 27001:2022 Clause 8.2 requires documented processes, procedures, and objective evidence of implementation. ISO 27002:2022 Control 8.6 demands incident documentation, analysis, and lessons learned. Comprehensive audit trail demonstrates conformity.",
      "justification_wrong": "Verbal explanations, external reports alone, or minimal notification do not satisfy ISO 27001:2022 requirements for documented, evidenced control implementation and continual improvement demonstrated through records."
    },
    {
      "num": 31,
      "text": "During an ISO 27001:2022 implementation, you must establish a risk assessment process. According to ISO/IEC 27005, which sequence correctly represents the risk assessment methodology?",
      "tag": "Risk Assessment & Treatment",
      "options": [
        "B. Risk identification → Context establishment → Risk analysis → Risk evaluation → Risk treatment",
        "D. Risk treatment → Risk analysis → Risk identification → Context establishment → Risk evaluation",
        "A. Context establishment → Risk identification → Risk analysis → Risk evaluation → Risk treatment",
